Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 14th Weekly Dose of Optimism. If you=E2=80=
=99re interested in how Not Boring has grown over the past few years, we di=
d a Twitter thread (sorry!) on the topic.=20
Long story short:=20
we=E2=80=99re still growing surprisingly fast despite no paid marketing=20
you are all still engaging with the content we put out despite the world op=
ening up (thank you!)=20
you are each (or at least in aggregate) very impressive people
advertisers still want to reach you in an authentic and effective way, and =
sponsoring Not Boring is a good way to do that
If you=E2=80=99re interested in more of the specifics and numbers, check ou=
t the thread (again, sorry, we hate ourselves too sometimes) below:
Now, let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) =F0=9F=8E=A7 [ https://substack.com/redirect/d8e74584-e9d1-4e73-93fc-59=
4af9545bd6?r=3D9p0gt ] We Know Shockingly Little About What Makes Humanity =
Prosper [ https://substack.com/redirect/13a6ce19-111f-4e23-8d3b-e35d18c796d=
4?r=3D9p0gt ] =F0=9F=8E=A7 [ https://substack.com/redirect/d8e74584-e9d1-4e=
73-93fc-594af9545bd6?r=3D9p0gt ]
From The Ezra Klein [ https://substack.com/redirect/b0edf70e-270f-4194-8584=
-b8ee8b0352e7?r=3D9p0gt ] Show
We all know Patrick Collison, the charmingly Irish and intellectual co-foun=
der and CEO of Stripe [ https://substack.com/redirect/4694f75b-cde4-4aaa-a7=
29-cd396b8c4bda?r=3D9p0gt ], the fourth most valuable privately held =E2=80=
=9Cstartup=E2=80=9D in the world. He=E2=80=99s lesser known for, but perhap=
s more influential in, the co-creation and support of Progress Studies. The=
 discipline, which was essentially written into existence by Collison and e=
conomist Tyler Cowen in this Atlantic piece titled, =E2=80=9CWe Need a New =
Science of Progress [ http://We Need a New Science of Progress ],=E2=80=9D =
studies the history, nature, and characteristics of human progress. The key=
 insight of Progress Studies is that progress is more fragile and uncertain=
 than it appears =E2=80=94and, given progress=E2=80=99 general importance i=
n=E2=80=A6everything=E2=80=A6, we should probably study it more closely.
Collison=E2=80=99s influence in this sphere =E2=80=94 thanks to his ~$10B n=
et worth, prestige within engineering circles, actual intellectual contribu=
tions, and novel funding approach =E2=80=94 probably outranks just about an=
yone else in the world. This whole podcast is worth a listen (or transcript=
 worth reading [ https://substack.com/redirect/bf4d7968-eaf7-41fb-ad74-1901=
c02ba41e?r=3D9p0gt ]) because it=E2=80=99s likely Collison=E2=80=99s most r=
obust articulation of his worldview.
If I had to sum up that worldview in a sentence: optimistic that we can con=
tinue to accelerate the rate of progress, if we understand its causes and i=
ntentionally create environments in which it can thrive.
BONUS: AN END TO DOOMERISM [ https://substack.com/redirect/47eb1697-f7a2-4b=
31-8e80-711b1c359278?r=3D9p0gt ]
Hannah Ritchie [ https://substack.com/redirect/101744b8-1078-4e88-82b5-5919=
478e402d?r=3D9p0gt ] for Big Think
Speaking of Progress Studies and Optimism, Hannah Ritchie=E2=80=94the head =
of Research at Our World in Data [ https://substack.com/redirect/cd615da7-a=
237-4ceb-944b-c21a2b0081a6?r=3D9p0gt ]=E2=80=94just came out as an optimist=
=2E Not a blind optimist, though. Hannah=20=
is too data-driven for that. She sub=
scribes to a more Not Boringian definition of optimism: =E2=80=9Chopefulnes=
s and confidence about the future or the success of something.=E2=80=9D Rit=
chie=E2=80=99s own optimistic worldview, I think, aligns quite closely with=
 Collison=E2=80=99s, and I know, pretty much 100% aligns with my own which =
I laid out in Optimism [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c678108-afba-4495-b=
cbd-a911ab803fac?r=3D9p0gt ].
(2) Eliud Kipchoge Lowers His Own Marathon World Record by Half a Minute [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/c1ab447c-ef63-4ac3-92ff-c0156f7a119a?r=3D9p0g=
t ]
Rachel Bachman [ https://substack.com/redirect/23389bbe-0d0f-46c0-9041-f9a3=
6ead6776?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Wall Street Journal
Speaking of progress, history=E2=80=99s fastest marathon runner just smashe=
d his own world record, clocking an official 2 hours, 1 minute, 9 seconds =
=E2=80=94 shaving 30 seconds off his 2018 time. Eliud Kipchoge (great profi=
le in  [ https://substack.com/redirect/f3aa1e6e-06a6-46a8-8857-239497a35fad=
?r=3D9p0gt ]The Irish Examiner [ https://substack.com/redirect/f3aa1e6e-06a=
6-46a8-8857-239497a35fad?r=3D9p0gt ]) is most widely known for being the fi=
rst runner to run 26.2 miles in under 2 hours, though that=E2=80=99s not an=
 official world record because the event was not an open competition, but r=
ather, was designed specifically for the breakthrough.
Like the 4 minute mile, the 2 hour marathon is an almost mythical threshold=
 that seems both physically and mentally unbreakable. But the 4 minute mile=
 falling was one of the all-time great proof points for the idea that when =
one person shows something is possible, all of the sudden, a lot of other p=
eople see that it=E2=80=99s possible. Kipchoge, or some other future marath=
on runner, breaking the 2 hour marathon would be a similar feat. Our guess =
is that when someone eventually breaks the barrier, a bunch of people are g=
oing to start running sub-2 in short order. A good reminder that impossible=
 things often aren=E2=80=99t.=20
(3) Wild mammals are making a comeback in Europe thanks to conservation eff=
orts [ https://substack.com/redirect/3b07054b-0590-494d-975f-7341e223ae5c?r=
=3D9p0gt ]
Hannah Ritchie [ https://substack.com/redirect/101744b8-1078-4e88-82b5-5919=
478e402d?r=3D9p0gt ] for Our World in Data
What these promising trends show is that the recovery of wildlife is possib=
le. Improvements in agricultural productivity not only halted the expansion=
 of agriculture, but eventually reversed it. Farmland was given back to nat=
ure. Importantly, Europe achieved this while producing more food [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/4342aca0-a5f0-49a0-b34a-bdc629b74e80?r=3D9p0gt ] at t=
he same time.
Not only are we making progress, we (and by =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=9D I mean hum=
ans and animals) are making comebacks! The same Hannah Ritchie from the bon=
us article above, shows how large mammals are once again flourishing in Eur=
ope thanks to conservation efforts. Take the European bison, for example: n=
early driven to extinction in the early 20th century due to hunting and hab=
itat loss, there are now nearly 10,000 in the wild.
Turns out, the easiest way to prevent animal extinction is to=E2=80=A6stop =
intentionally killing them. But beyond a decline in hunting, conservation, =
reintroduction, and wildlife protections programs have allowed these once e=
ndangered species to flourish again.
(4) NASA crashes DART spacecraft into asteroid in world's 1st planetary def=
ense test [ https://substack.com/redirect/56e103bb-64e3-4ec0-a8e2-0b05bd837=
ed7?r=3D9p0gt ]
Tariq Malik [ https://substack.com/redirect/d30bb958-dc95-4724-9042-b9bbfe1=
5eecd?r=3D9p0gt ] for Space.com
If we humans are progressing and animals are making a comeback, it=E2=80=99=
d be a damn shame if some asteroid plummeted out of space into earth causin=
g serious environmental damage, mass extinction, and generally devastating =
civilization beyond repair =E2=80=94 wouldn=E2=80=99t it?
Fear not =E2=80=94 we have a plan: smashing miniature spacecraft into oncom=
ing asteroids. NASA=E2=80=99s DART Mission=E2=80=99s (Google it, the search=
 results page [ https://substack.com/redirect/103ed7b2-dd3b-46c9-8450-405fc=
3f80c24?r=3D9p0gt ] is fun!) objective is to test methods of planetary defe=
nse against near-Earth objects, like asteroids and other various space obje=
cts. Essentially, how can we deflect oncoming objects off their trajectory =
such that they miss crashing into earth.
This first mission seems to have been a success, but to be fair, the stakes=
 were relatively low: even if the mission failed, the asteroid was never de=
stined for earth. As an aside, nothing gets me pumped up like a bunch of NA=
SA nerds cheering, high-fiving, and fisting-pumping over some grainy, hard-=
to-understand-what=E2=80=99s-actually-going-on video =E2=80=94 it means we =
still have people out there that are truly jazzed up about space. We need m=
ore of those folks.
(5) The Future History of the Nuclear Renaissance With Isabelle Boemeke [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/23d9355e-a725-4ae4-b3c9-dd42f04d14f9?r=3D9p0gt=
 ]
By Isabelle Boemke [ https://substack.com/redirect/0218da8f-37d7-493b-a241-=
bb89714c0c5a?r=3D9p0gt ] for Palladium
In =E2=80=9CThe Enchanted Notebook [ https://substack.com/redirect/e85d9067=
-8cb0-444e-ac3f-fa5724906e1a?r=3D9p0gt ]=E2=80=9D we wrote that one way to =
create the future is to imagine it, write it down, and reverse engineer how=
 we got there. Isabelle Boemke does just that in this piece: imagine a worl=
d 30 years in the future in which a nuclear renaissance has made energy che=
ap and abundant, detail exactly what that world looks like, and reverse eng=
ineer what must=E2=80=99ve happened to get there. Here=E2=80=99s how Boemke=
 breaks it down:
Catalyst 1: War between Russia and Ukraine makes West remember (once again)=
 that energy independence is important.
Catalyst 2: As energy abundance is embraced, governments realize they reall=
y only have two options: double-down on coal or embrace nuclear.
Catalyst 3: It becomes politically popular to embrace coal =E2=80=94 the hy=
pocrisy of the 20th century around nuclear becomes clear, first to activist=
s, then to the general population.
Catalysts 4: Governments that embrace nuclear early and hard are put in a p=
osition of leadership.
Who knows exactly how the future will play out, but this seems like a relat=
ively believable path =E2=80=94 and one worth trying to re-create in the re=
al world. We=E2=80=99re already seeing some of these catalysts play out and=
 nuclear momentum is starting to leak out of the activist circles into live=
s of everyday folks that just want cleaner, cheaper, and more abundant ener=
gy.
Bonus: The World=E2=80=99s Fair Co. Posters [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/a9da5e68-fd10-4f8e-8a58-84272273db1c?r=3D9p0gt ]
Speaking of painting a picture of the future you want to see, The World=E2=
=80=99s Fair Co., released posters in collaboration with Invisible Creature=
 (the folks behind the NASA Visions posters [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/cf284169-b171-4462-8df9-3debee1886a7?r=3D9p0gt ]) that depict the future o=
f different sectors of the economy: space, AI, crypto, food, oceans, clean =
energy, health, robotics, cities, travel, and science.=20
The World=E2=80=99s Fair Co. is one of our favorite projects here at Not Bo=
ring. As the name suggests, founder Cam Wiese [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/d2938224-1c38-4952-b2b5-e72a52e8e350?r=3D9p0gt ] & co are bringing back =
The World=E2=80=99s Fair in order to bring an optimistic vision of the futu=
re to life. At the Fair, =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99ll see and interact with the =
technologies of today that are shaping the world of tomorrow.=E2=80=9D It=
=E2=80=99s a crazily ambitious project =E2=80=94 the kind I=E2=80=99m thril=
led to see people pursuing =E2=80=94 and I can=E2=80=99t wait to attend tow=
ards the end of the decade when they pull it off.
You can check out the full gallery (and buy prints of the posters, I picked=
 up =E2=80=9CWelcome to the Future=E2=80=9D) here [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/a9da5e68-fd10-4f8e-8a58-84272273db1c?r=3D9p0gt ], and check out the =
whole shiny new site here [ https://substack.com/redirect/a03aee18-385b-4a8=
f-822a-088111ff3909?r=3D9p0gt ].
I=E2=80=99ll leave you with this quote from The World=E2=80=99s Fair Co.=E2=
=80=99s Mission Statement [ https://substack.com/redirect/4936942c-41c7-491=
e-8343-c5b27115b8e0?r=3D9p0gt ]:
If we choose to aim high and build, future generations will live in a world=
 of abundance, progress, human flourishing, and beauty.
To achieve this vision, we must first create a culture that believes our fu=
ture is worth fighting for. We must tell stories about the future that empo=
wer us =E2=80=94 stories of a world that we're excited to live in and are i=
nspired to build.
Humans are pulling off some pretty incredible things every week. Whenever y=
ou find examples, share them here [ https://substack.com/redirect/1ffd8ffb-=
b0d3-42df-aced-476909dc9d70?r=3D9p0gt ] and we=E2=80=99ll feature some in t=
he newsletter.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week =E2=80=94 I=E2=80=99ll be back in your inb=
ox right before 9am EST on Monday morning. Enjoy the weekend.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

